185
00:25:51,971 --> 00:25:56,358
I'm only speaking now about unwholesome karma, but there is, remember, wholesome karma.

186
00:25:57,160 --> 00:26:04,230
So you've got karma which comes out of love, compassion, sympathetic joy, reciprocal joy.

187
00:26:06,492 --> 00:26:10,218
And that, of course, would develop the better side of us.

188
00:26:10,759 --> 00:26:11,400
So...

189
00:26:12,628 --> 00:26:14,411
As always comes this intention.

190
00:26:14,770 --> 00:26:23,161
Now one of the things that I haven't particularly pushed on this retreat, but I would do so on a full Mahasi, is really noting intentions.

191
00:26:24,363 --> 00:26:28,146
So there's the noting, but it's the noting of intention which is so crucial.

192
00:26:28,647 --> 00:26:30,088
Intending to open the door.

193
00:26:30,809 --> 00:26:31,891
Intending to eat.

194
00:26:31,931 --> 00:26:34,974
The fact that you're saying it is the intention.

195
00:26:35,646 --> 00:26:46,539
And what we're trying to understand is that even the smallest action, even me doing this business, you know, shaking my hands about, even that has some intention in it.

196
00:26:46,980 --> 00:26:51,444
Even if it's only subliminal, there must have been some intention.

197
00:26:52,707 --> 00:27:03,138
There's a lovely example of that given in the Visuddhimagga, which is a sort of later work, but it's seen as a sort of...

198
00:27:03,457 --> 00:27:09,204
It's Theravada Buddhism, it's written by a monk that was called Buddhaghosa.

199
00:27:10,365 --> 00:27:21,520
And in it he talks about, there was a teacher giving a talk, and suddenly he raised his hand and stopped talking, and then in silence he put his hand back, you see.

200
00:27:22,522 --> 00:27:23,624
So the student said, what happened?

201
00:27:26,528 --> 00:27:29,531
He said, I didn't note the intention of moving my hand.

202
00:27:30,388 --> 00:27:31,750
That's how, you see?

203
00:27:31,769 --> 00:27:34,692
So you can see how advanced he was compared to me.

204
00:27:35,733 --> 00:27:36,954
I haven't a clue what I'm doing, mate.

205
00:27:37,555 --> 00:27:41,519
So it's catching this intention.

206
00:27:42,038 --> 00:27:46,163
Now, every intention, once it's empowered, becomes an action.

207
00:27:47,104 --> 00:27:47,924
Okay?

208
00:27:47,944 --> 00:27:49,986
So if you intend to open the door, you open the door.

209
00:27:50,007 --> 00:27:52,648
Now, there's nothing particularly ethical about that.

210
00:27:54,851 --> 00:27:56,092
It's just opening the door.

211
00:27:58,334 --> 00:27:59,535
But...

212
00:28:00,712 --> 00:28:29,269
every action produces a habit so that after a while you definitely know how to open doors and remember that opening a door here should have an existential quality about it it's not the case of just opening the door it's the case of doing it very slowly and recognising that you've actually moved out of a different space you've become somebody else on the other side of the door even though it's not

213
00:28:30,008 --> 00:28:57,535
not so obvious so it's it's actually recognizing that from an intention that comes an action and then you create a habit okay so if you um if you decide uh that you know that you come home and you're going to watch the news on the tv then once you've done it and you enjoy it the next day you come back and do it and then after a while it's just something you do it becomes habitual

214
00:28:59,809 --> 00:29:05,417
If you put all these habits together, the sankhara, then what you have is your personality.

215
00:29:06,720 --> 00:29:08,742
In Buddhism, that's your personality and character.

216
00:29:08,923 --> 00:29:11,166
It's a set of habits.

217
00:29:11,186 --> 00:29:11,807
That's all it is.

218
00:29:13,530 --> 00:29:19,480
And once that's set, as it were, your destiny is ahead of you, you see.

219
00:29:22,163 --> 00:29:27,612
And it's only when we keep falling over that we might wake up and think, well, what about these habits I've got?

220
00:29:27,632 --> 00:29:28,432
Maybe I should...

221
00:29:28,732 --> 00:29:30,776
Maybe we should change a few of them.

222
00:29:30,796 --> 00:29:32,519
And that's of course the practice we're in.

223
00:29:33,240 --> 00:29:39,229
Trying to move away from those habits which causes problems to those which are beautiful.

224
00:29:40,130 --> 00:29:46,180
So that's the process of karma in the sense of an action.

225
00:29:50,506 --> 00:29:57,676
Now the other thing that we have to remember is that it's those actions which have an ethical value which are important.

226
00:29:58,837 --> 00:30:02,541
So if we remember the story of the Buddha again, there were three knowledges.

227
00:30:02,682 --> 00:30:05,486
The first one was that he was purified.

228
00:30:05,546 --> 00:30:10,531
There were no more unwholesome mental qualities in him.

229
00:30:11,352 --> 00:30:19,060
And that he saw how he came to this position through a series of past lives driven by his ethical decisions.

230
00:30:19,741 --> 00:30:23,567
And then he saw other beings moving around in the same way.

231
00:30:24,508 --> 00:30:28,271
So ethics is, in other words,

232
00:30:28,758 --> 00:30:39,790
Our whole relationship to human beings, to buildings, to trees, everything else, that is our ethics.

233
00:30:39,810 --> 00:30:42,314
That's what we mean that Buddha meant by ethics.

234
00:30:42,814 --> 00:30:45,057
It's not just a simple case of morality.

235
00:30:45,817 --> 00:30:48,340
It's not just a simple case of doing right and wrong.

236
00:30:49,001 --> 00:30:54,387
It's a case of how do we relate to everything that we meet.

237
00:30:54,407 --> 00:30:55,890
And of course that includes ourselves.

238
00:30:56,711 --> 00:30:58,613
How do I relate to myself?

239
00:30:58,913 --> 00:31:27,282
so when I said that it's only opening a door it can be done gently and then it becomes an ethical opening of the door it can be done angrily and then it becomes an unethical opening of the door so then you realise that everything you do everything you do really has an ethical value to it and that's when you get worried

240
00:31:29,423 --> 00:31:39,837
because that's our conditioning and the conditioning is driving us to a certain destiny either to happiness or unhappiness

241
00:31:41,692 --> 00:31:46,898
So that gives us some idea of the thrust of karma.

242
00:31:47,338 --> 00:31:48,381
It's the ethics.

243
00:31:49,021 --> 00:32:07,205
So if the first law was about just the physics of the universe, the chemistry of it, and the second one is hereditary, and the third one all to do with our psychology, and the fifth one to do with the spiritual practices, the spiritual laws, this fourth one, karma, is specific around ethics.

244
00:32:07,286 --> 00:32:08,307
It's about ethics.

245
00:32:09,433 --> 00:32:17,365
It's about how and why we behave the way we do.

246
00:32:17,384 --> 00:32:22,791
So this means that it's impossible to grow in wisdom and behave unethically.

247
00:32:23,712 --> 00:32:27,798
It can't be that jarring, you know.

248
00:32:27,818 --> 00:32:31,163
Can you imagine, you know, catching the Buddha shoplifting?

249
00:32:32,325 --> 00:32:33,625
It wouldn't work, would it?

250
00:32:33,645 --> 00:32:36,369
You'd have to think, well, hold on, he said he was enlightened.

251
00:32:38,459 --> 00:33:07,875
it's just there are certain things that just don't fit once we have this image this archetype of a Buddha of somebody who's completely purified and then the last thing really is to understand that nothing is set so that when we do an action and we can see it wasn't particularly good we can always stop the consequences of it so remember an action will have its consequences

252
00:33:08,125 --> 00:33:34,403
as soon as you act you're putting an energy of force into a matrix and you don't know how it's going to happen I think I mentioned it before I couldn't remember the physics for it but I'm sure you've heard of the chaos the theory of chaos where one small action with supporting conditions can just go out of proportion so

253
00:33:34,567 --> 00:33:37,391
The thing you're always given is always dramatic.

254
00:33:37,451 --> 00:33:45,259
A butterfly wing in South America, huge storm in North America because of the surrounding conditions.

255
00:33:45,980 --> 00:34:02,279
But I think we can also see it in a slightly more optimistic light that one small act of kindness done somewhere could bring peace in some other part of the world because you don't know what the effect of that will be

256
00:34:02,767 --> 00:34:18,326
you know, just like, again, on the negative side, the straw that broke the camel's back, see, just a little small act of goodwill put into a particular situation can have these wondrous effects.

257
00:34:20,648 --> 00:34:26,956
So, on the positive side, that's why, you know, we should obviously do good things.

258
00:34:27,637 --> 00:34:30,039
On the negative side, when you do something,

259
00:34:30,322 --> 00:34:57,192
you know it's going to have an effect something negative you know it's going to have an effect so just very simply often with friends at work or in other situations we might say something which has been taken wrongly we might not even have meant it to be an insult it doesn't have to be that you actually mean to do something it could have been something that wasn't quite meant or

260
00:34:57,695 --> 00:35:00,960
wasn't the right thing to say at that time.

261
00:35:01,581 --> 00:35:09,532
So remember that when the Buddha talks about right speech, he talks about it being kindly, being honest, but also a suitable time.

262
00:35:11,094 --> 00:35:12,978
You have to choose your time to say certain things.

263
00:35:14,280 --> 00:35:17,965
And of course that can create a lot of upset, a lot of animosity.

264
00:35:18,467 --> 00:35:45,807
even worse and it can reverberate back on you so it's a case of as soon as we know we've done something is to do something to bring that process to an end often a simple apology will do we had a wonderful case here so I'll come towards an end on this we had an oak tree and

265
00:35:46,277 --> 00:35:48,480
And it used to overhang the back of the garden here.

266
00:35:49,340 --> 00:35:52,364
And we had to get rid of it, unfortunately, because of the oil tank.

267
00:35:52,784 --> 00:35:57,369
There was all sorts of health and safety reasons around oil tanks.

268
00:35:57,389 --> 00:36:06,619
And I had this expert come, who used to be in competitions in Colombia, chopping trees down.

269
00:36:06,639 --> 00:36:09,561
And he really was quite an expert.

270
00:36:09,581 --> 00:36:14,007
Anyway, one of our neighbours saw this and he came over

271
00:36:14,695 --> 00:36:23,364
I was in the kitchen, I was just coming into the kitchen, and sounded this awesome row, I mean really a lot of anger.

272
00:36:23,985 --> 00:36:31,032
So I go out there, and of course I'm terribly peaceful and equanimous, you see, because I'm not involved.

273
00:36:33,835 --> 00:36:36,777
So I can play the peacemaker, you know.

274
00:36:36,838 --> 00:36:38,880
And I'm saying, what's going on, you see.

275
00:36:39,097 --> 00:36:50,248
And basically, he'd come over and had questioned the fact as to whether we could take down an oak tree, because some of them are guarded, you see.

276
00:36:50,528 --> 00:36:52,331
There was a neighbour here who knocked an oak tree down.

277
00:36:52,791 --> 00:36:54,012
He was fined 2,000 quid.

278
00:36:55,092 --> 00:36:59,557
And he somehow got it wrong in his head that it wasn't our oak tree.

279
00:36:59,617 --> 00:37:00,858
It was all a bit funny.

280
00:37:00,878 --> 00:37:06,284
But anyway, the lumberjack, who was okay, by the way, he...

281
00:37:06,907 --> 00:37:09,394
He said something that was really upsetting.

282
00:37:09,454 --> 00:37:16,637
And he came out with this stunning phrase, which must go into the annals of great phrases.

283
00:37:16,657 --> 00:37:19,887
He says, I'm from Liverpool and I'll have you shot.

284
00:37:24,119 --> 00:37:27,103
So I thought, that is absolutely brilliant.

285
00:37:27,824 --> 00:37:36,014
So anyway, as it happened, I was able to sort of calm him down to some spot.

286
00:37:37,135 --> 00:37:42,402
This lumberjack, by the way, who wasn't a particularly big man, but he had a couple of big young fellas with him.

287
00:37:42,902 --> 00:37:46,025
So the neighbour sort of, he's still raging.

288
00:37:46,347 --> 00:37:47,527
And eventually...

289
00:37:48,588 --> 00:37:56,375
the lumberjack said to him, look, he said, you know, you just threatened me, you just threatened my life, you know, and I've got witnesses, you know.

290
00:37:57,355 --> 00:38:00,538
So he said, so finally he said, look, just a simple apology will do.

291
00:38:00,838 --> 00:38:07,963
And finally, the neighbour, when he'd all calmed down, he said, sorry, and sort of went out with his tail between his legs.

292
00:38:07,983 --> 00:38:09,965
It was sort of a wonderful occasion.

293
00:38:09,985 --> 00:38:11,246
I wish it had been filmed.

294
00:38:12,867 --> 00:38:18,072
So, in that case, you see, you've got a neighbour who knows nothing about Buddhism.

295
00:38:18,092 --> 00:38:18,492
He's like,

296
00:38:18,844 --> 00:38:20,306
He was a million miles away from it.

297
00:38:20,786 --> 00:38:25,050
But he recognised that at some point he'd gone overboard.

298
00:38:25,490 --> 00:38:29,974
He'd lost his, he'd lost a certain equanimity, we can say.

299
00:38:30,976 --> 00:38:35,981
And just by that simple, very simple apology, it was, that was it, you know.

300
00:38:36,722 --> 00:38:47,552
I'm sure they don't meet for a drink now and again, but at least the consequences of what, you know, of that was just brought to an end, you know.

301
00:38:51,228 --> 00:39:01,219
So, just to summarize there, just so that we're clear about what the Buddha's teaching about karma.

302
00:39:01,239 --> 00:39:05,463
Not everything that happens to us is to do with our personal karma.

303
00:39:06,063 --> 00:39:11,769
And even if something happens to us, it may only be a part of that which is our personal karma.

304
00:39:12,690 --> 00:39:18,197
It may only be a small part of it.

305
00:39:18,717 --> 00:39:31,137
So, I mean, in terms of, you know, our neighbour, the fact that he got involved in that was part of his original goodness, you know, trying to save trees, for heaven's sake.

306
00:39:31,157 --> 00:39:32,659
I mean, that's where he was coming from.

307
00:39:34,322 --> 00:39:36,827
But it got him into this embroilment, you know.

308
00:39:38,900 --> 00:39:54,525
And the fact that the lumberjack didn't take huge offense and cut his legs off with his chainsaw was good.

309
00:39:58,030 --> 00:40:04,501
Could have got pretty nasty, you know.

310
00:40:05,967 --> 00:40:14,755
There are different laws which we're accustomed to, the physical and the hereditary and the psychological and the spiritual laws.

311
00:40:14,775 --> 00:40:19,380
All these things are almost in every moment of our lives.

312
00:40:19,599 --> 00:40:29,630
If you take any moment, you'll see that there's a physicality to it, there's a mentality to it, there's a hereditary part of it.

313
00:40:29,710 --> 00:40:33,052
It's not as though these things are either not there, they're always there.

314
00:40:33,233 --> 00:40:34,353
These laws are always there.

315
00:40:34,722 --> 00:40:41,289
And even if we're not aware of the spiritual laws, we're probably going against them and creating havoc because of it.

316
00:40:41,768 --> 00:40:43,431
And one of them is this law of karma.

317
00:40:43,590 --> 00:40:52,519
It's just brought out of the spiritual laws because it's a very specific avenue of teaching.

318
00:40:54,322 --> 00:40:59,768
And then the idea that we don't live in a predestined universe.

319
00:40:59,827 --> 00:41:01,188
Nobody knows what happens.

320
00:41:01,248 --> 00:41:03,851
The Buddha said if you try to work out your karma, you'll drive you mad.

321
00:41:06,329 --> 00:41:09,833
So we don't know what's going to happen next in any absolute sense.

322
00:41:10,994 --> 00:41:12,396
But that gives us creativity.

323
00:41:12,577 --> 00:41:13,639
It gives us destruction.

324
00:41:14,320 --> 00:41:16,382
Everything is destroyed and then created.

325
00:41:18,244 --> 00:41:22,090
It's interesting that in Hinduism you have Brahma the creator.

326
00:41:22,811 --> 00:41:26,416
But then you have Shiva the destroyer, don't you?

327
00:41:26,436 --> 00:41:31,061
And Vishnu, the one who creates.

328
00:41:33,065 --> 00:41:33,626
I think that's it.

329
00:41:33,885 --> 00:41:34,766
I'm not sure now.

330
00:41:35,269 --> 00:41:42,159
But anyway, it's that business of there's always an ending and then there's a beginning.

331
00:41:42,521 --> 00:41:44,083
An ending and a beginning.

332
00:41:44,364 --> 00:41:47,268
Something has to be destroyed for something to be born.

333
00:41:48,369 --> 00:41:52,155
And that's just part and parcel of it.

334
00:41:52,175 --> 00:41:58,483
And our process, our spiritual process, is this process of purification.

335
00:42:00,447 --> 00:42:03,572
And you can come...

336
00:42:03,771 --> 00:42:15,704
The Eightfold Path starts off with right understanding, which affects our attitudes, which affects the way we speak and what we do and our livelihood.

337
00:42:16,085 --> 00:42:19,088
But remember, it can also, it comes back on itself as feedback.

338
00:42:19,690 --> 00:42:26,516
So there are many livelihoods which have in themselves the potential for compassion.

339
00:42:26,556 --> 00:42:33,744
In fact, all livelihood, apart from those which are obviously unwholesome, have

340
00:42:33,978 --> 00:42:36,721
the quality of service about them.

341
00:42:36,740 --> 00:42:38,583
And I'll probably say more about that tomorrow.

342
00:42:39,043 --> 00:42:46,572
And it's this quality of service that's coming through the heart, through the attitude, which then becomes a wisdom.

343
00:42:47,172 --> 00:42:52,338
So the distinction between compassion, love and wisdom is just they're two sides of the same coin.

344
00:42:52,858 --> 00:42:55,302
You can't have wisdom without the expression of compassion.

345
00:42:56,123 --> 00:42:58,025
And you can't have compassion unless you've got the wisdom.

346
00:42:59,166 --> 00:43:01,909
So compassion is wisdom in action, you see.

347
00:43:02,632 --> 00:43:21,365
so everything in that sense is connected so there's a part of us which is investigating but also the part of us which is doing things is crucially important to this whole process of purification liberation and the awakening the process of awakening

348
00:43:28,432 --> 00:43:31,458
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

349
00:43:31,657 --> 00:43:46,559
May you by your severe practice attain full liberation from all suffering sooner rather than later.

